<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Programming on Kvn11</title><link>https://Kvn11.github.io/tags/programming/</link><description>Recent content in Programming on Kvn11</description><generator>Hugo -- gohugo.io</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Sun, 19 May 2024 02:45:01 -0700</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://Kvn11.github.io/tags/programming/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Intro To Kernel Exploitation</title><link>https://Kvn11.github.io/p/intro-to-kernel-exploitation/</link><pubDate>Sun, 19 May 2024 02:45:01 -0700</pubDate><guid>https://Kvn11.github.io/p/intro-to-kernel-exploitation/</guid><description>&lt;img src="https://i.pinimg.com/564x/05/2e/8d/052e8d59f511fd32a620ce1d12da0aa3.jpg" alt="Featured image of post Intro To Kernel Exploitation" />&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>Disclaimer: This is an active work in progress, things might be wrong, or might not make sense.
These are pretty much just notes until I finish and clean it up.&lt;/p>
&lt;/blockquote>
&lt;h2 id="background-info">Background Info
&lt;/h2>&lt;h3 id="vuln">Vuln
&lt;/h3>&lt;p>The vulnerability to exploit today is: &lt;a class="link" href="https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2022-27666" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>CVE-2022-27666&lt;/a>.
I just randomly picked this one out from the &lt;a class="link" href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1a9uUAISBzw3ur1aLQqKc5JOQLaJYiOP5pe_B4xCT1KA/edit#heading=h.9c6s9d5wfjju" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>Google Recipes Notebook&lt;/a>.
There a few PoC&amp;rsquo;s for this vulnerability online, which is good because if I get stuck at some point, I can take a look, but the goal is to develop an exploit all on my own.
The advisory says:&lt;/p>
&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>A heap buffer overflow flaw was found in IPsec ESP transformation code in &lt;code>net/ipv4/esp4.c&lt;/code> and &lt;code>net/ipv6/esp6.c&lt;/code>.
This flaw allows a local attacker with a normal user privilege to overwrite kernel heap objects and may cause a local privilege escalation threat.&lt;/p>
&lt;/blockquote>
&lt;p>The vuln appears in the function &lt;code>int esp_output_head(struct xfrm_state *x, struct sk_buff *skb, struct esp_info *esp)&lt;/code>.
&lt;code>ESP_SKB_FRAG_MAXSIZE&lt;/code> is defined as &lt;code>(PAGE_SIZE &amp;lt;&amp;lt; SKB_FRAG_PAGE_ORDER)&lt;/code>.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>The commit that is linked in the advisory adds a fix to check whether the len of the &lt;code>skb-&amp;gt;data_len + tailen&lt;/code> is greater than &lt;code>(PAGE_SIZE &amp;lt;&amp;lt; SKB_FRAG_PAGE_ORDER)&lt;/code>.
This leads to a hardcoded value being set as the len of the buffer to be encrypted, which can then be taken advantage via other memcpy operations.&lt;/p>
&lt;h3 id="setup">Setup
&lt;/h3>&lt;p>I recommend you use an Ubuntu VM for this, I had issues developing on Kali.
We can start by setting up github.
After you download the linux repo, switch to the vulnerable version / tag with:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div class="chroma">
&lt;table class="lntable">&lt;tr>&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code>&lt;span class="lnt">1
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-fallback" data-lang="fallback">&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">git checkout -b CVE-2022-2766 v5.16
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>This will create a branch named &lt;code>CVE-2022-2766&lt;/code> which will contain all the content within the &lt;code>v5.16&lt;/code> commit, which is the last vulnerable version.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>We can then more or less follow the instructions &lt;a class="link" href="https://kernw0lf.github.io/posts/qemu_debug/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>given here by kernw0lf&lt;/a>.
Create a default config file with &lt;code>make defconfig&lt;/code>.
Then we add a few more extra settings to help with debugging:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div class="chroma">
&lt;table class="lntable">&lt;tr>&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code>&lt;span class="lnt">1
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">2
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">3
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">4
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">5
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">6
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-fallback" data-lang="fallback">&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">CONFIG_KCOV=y
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">CONFIG_DEBUG_INFO=y
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">CONFIG_KASAN=y
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">CONFIG_KASAN_INLINE=y
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">CONFIG_CONFIGFS_FS=y
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">CONFIG_SECURITYFS=y
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>Additionally, there are a few other options you have to enable, but for brevity you can access the correct config file at my repo &lt;a class="link" href="https://github.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>here&lt;/a>.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Then compile with &lt;code>make -j$(nproc)&lt;/code>.
Next you have to download the ubuntu cloud iso.
I tried getting this to work with busybox, as I wanted a barebones system so I can focus on just this vulnerability, but after several days of struggling I gave in and opted for this method you&amp;rsquo;ll see below.
First, download a recent minimal Ubuntu cloud image from &lt;a class="link" href="https://cloud-images.ubuntu.com/minimal/releases/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>here&lt;/a>:&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Then you need to configure the users, set up ssh keys, etc:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div class="chroma">
&lt;table class="lntable">&lt;tr>&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code>&lt;span class="lnt"> 1
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 2
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 3
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 4
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 5
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 6
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 7
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 8
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 9
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">10
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">11
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">12
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">13
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">14
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">sudo apt-get install libguestfs-tools
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">virt-customize -a /path/to/ubuntu.img &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> --run-command &lt;span class="s1">&amp;#39;apt-get update&amp;#39;&lt;/span> &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> --install ssh-server &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> --install strongswan &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> --install vim &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> --run-command &lt;span class="s1">&amp;#39;systemctl enable ssh&amp;#39;&lt;/span> &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> --root-password password:root &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> --ssh-inject root:file:/path/to/root/ssh.pub &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> --run-command &lt;span class="s1">&amp;#39;useradd -m -s /bin/bash pwn&amp;#39;&lt;/span> &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> --password pwn:password:abc123 &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> --ssh-inject pwn:file:/path/to/pwn/ssh.pub &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> --copy-in /lib/modules/5.16.0:/lib/modules/
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>Then we can run the image like:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div class="chroma">
&lt;table class="lntable">&lt;tr>&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code>&lt;span class="lnt"> 1
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 2
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 3
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 4
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 5
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 6
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 7
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 8
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 9
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">10
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">11
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="cp">#!/bin/bash
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="cp">&lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">qemu-system-x86_64 &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> -m 2G &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> -smp &lt;span class="m">2&lt;/span> &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> -kernel ./bzImage &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> -drive &lt;span class="nv">file&lt;/span>&lt;span class="o">=&lt;/span>./ubuntu-20.10-minimal-cloudimg-amd64.img &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> -append &lt;span class="s2">&amp;#34;root=/dev/sda1 rw console=ttyS0&amp;#34;&lt;/span> &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> -nographic &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> -netdev user,id&lt;span class="o">=&lt;/span>net0,hostfwd&lt;span class="o">=&lt;/span>tcp::2222-:22 &lt;span class="se">\
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="se">&lt;/span> -device virtio-net,netdev&lt;span class="o">=&lt;/span>net0
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>After logging in, verify that &lt;code>strongswan&lt;/code> is running with:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div class="chroma">
&lt;table class="lntable">&lt;tr>&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code>&lt;span class="lnt">1
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">systemctl status strongswan-starter
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;h3 id="networking">Networking
&lt;/h3>&lt;p>We also need set up IPSec&amp;rsquo;s config on the guest to ensure we are creating IPSEC packets.
For this purpose I&amp;rsquo;ll create a &amp;ldquo;non-working&amp;rdquo; configuration, but it should be enough for our exploit.
Add the following files:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div class="chroma">
&lt;table class="lntable">&lt;tr>&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code>&lt;span class="lnt">1
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">2
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">3
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">4
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">5
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">6
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">7
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">8
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">9
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-fallback" data-lang="fallback">&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl"># Added to /etc/ipsec.conf
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">conn local-to-fake
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl"> left=&amp;lt;qemu ip&amp;gt;
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl"> right=&amp;lt;host ip&amp;gt;
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl"> leftsubnet=&amp;lt;qemu subnet&amp;gt;
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl"> rightsubnet=&amp;lt;host subnet&amp;gt;
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl"> authby=secret
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl"> auto=start
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div class="chroma">
&lt;table class="lntable">&lt;tr>&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code>&lt;span class="lnt">1
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">2
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">3
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-fallback" data-lang="fallback">&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl"># Added to /etc/ipsec.secrets
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&amp;lt;qemu ip&amp;gt; &amp;lt;host ip&amp;gt; : PSK &amp;#34;secret&amp;#34;
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>Theres a bit more setup still, but basically you have to create a bridged network between qemu and your host, and then assign your qemu instance an IP.
I will come back later and update this section with the correct config.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>You can test whether the IPSEC packets are sending with tcpdump:&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://Kvn11.github.io/p/intro-to-kernel-exploitation/img/1.PNG"
width="874"
height="148"
srcset="https://Kvn11.github.io/p/intro-to-kernel-exploitation/img/1_hu9a2e99824327ac25abae96905a31fe54_27960_480x0_resize_box_3.PNG 480w, https://Kvn11.github.io/p/intro-to-kernel-exploitation/img/1_hu9a2e99824327ac25abae96905a31fe54_27960_1024x0_resize_box_3.PNG 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt="ESP Packets captured with tcpdump"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="590"
data-flex-basis="1417px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;h3 id="struct-esp_info">struct esp_info
&lt;/h3>&lt;p>This structure manages state information related to the ESP packet processing.
It&amp;rsquo;s important to understand this structure because we need certain values to be set in order to trigger the vulnerable code down the line.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://Kvn11.github.io/p/intro-to-kernel-exploitation/img/esp_info.png"
width="336"
height="326"
srcset="https://Kvn11.github.io/p/intro-to-kernel-exploitation/img/esp_info_hu3c716decee474d4070a712a3e9e54e3f_11729_480x0_resize_box_3.png 480w, https://Kvn11.github.io/p/intro-to-kernel-exploitation/img/esp_info_hu3c716decee474d4070a712a3e9e54e3f_11729_1024x0_resize_box_3.png 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt="include/net/esp.h"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="103"
data-flex-basis="247px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>The important values here are &lt;code>tailen&lt;/code>, &lt;code>tfclen&lt;/code>, &lt;code>plen&lt;/code>, and &lt;code>alen&lt;/code>.
We need &lt;code>tailen&lt;/code> to be greater than 0, and &lt;code>tailen&lt;/code> is calculated based on these other values.&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>&lt;code>tfclen&lt;/code> = transports format checksum length.&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;code>plen&lt;/code> = payload length, doesn&amp;rsquo;t include any padding or ESP header / trailer.&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;code>alen&lt;/code> = &lt;code>authsize&lt;/code> which in our case is 16.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;h3 id="struct-sk_buff">struct sk_buff
&lt;/h3>&lt;h3 id="struct-xfrm_state">struct xfrm_state
&lt;/h3>&lt;p>TODO:
Need to set `tfcpad to a non-zero value&lt;/p>
&lt;h2 id="techniques">Techniques
&lt;/h2>&lt;h2 id="poc">PoC
&lt;/h2>&lt;h2 id="notes">Notes
&lt;/h2>&lt;h3 id="testing">testing
&lt;/h3>&lt;p>Once you verify that your IPSEC tunnel is up and running, then continuing in GDB should hit your breakpoint relatively quickly.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://Kvn11.github.io/p/intro-to-kernel-exploitation/img/2.PNG"
width="1382"
height="402"
srcset="https://Kvn11.github.io/p/intro-to-kernel-exploitation/img/2_hu1d3f2a43cf72bdb7f079548931457122_62639_480x0_resize_box_3.PNG 480w, https://Kvn11.github.io/p/intro-to-kernel-exploitation/img/2_hu1d3f2a43cf72bdb7f079548931457122_62639_1024x0_resize_box_3.PNG 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt=" esp_output_head has been triggered. "
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="343"
data-flex-basis="825px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>We can view the value of our argument of interest with:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div class="chroma">
&lt;table class="lntable">&lt;tr>&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code>&lt;span class="lnt">1
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-fallback" data-lang="fallback">&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">(gdb) print *(struct sk_buff *)&amp;lt;address of sk_buff&amp;gt;
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>Now it should be saved in &lt;code>$1&lt;/code>.
So you can access &lt;code>data_len&lt;/code>, &lt;code>len&lt;/code> and &lt;code>tail_len&lt;/code> the same way you would in c:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div class="chroma">
&lt;table class="lntable">&lt;tr>&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code>&lt;span class="lnt">1
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">2
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">3
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-fallback" data-lang="fallback">&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">(gdb) p $1-&amp;gt;data_len
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">(gdb) p $1-&amp;gt;len
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">(gdb) p $1-&amp;gt;tailen
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>There is an important distinction to mention here before &lt;code>data_len&lt;/code> and &lt;code>len&lt;/code>.
&lt;code>Len&lt;/code> is the total size of our buffer.
&lt;code>data_len&lt;/code> is the paged size of our packet.
In other words, if our payload is large enough, then we will require it to store in big blocks of memory called &amp;ldquo;pages&amp;rdquo;.
If it is small enough to store within contiguous memory, then &lt;code>data_len&lt;/code> will be 0 because we don&amp;rsquo;t need to allocate large chunks of memory for it.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://Kvn11.github.io/p/intro-to-kernel-exploitation/img/3.PNG"
width="1830"
height="420"
srcset="https://Kvn11.github.io/p/intro-to-kernel-exploitation/img/3_hu55927aa20e4b1936546e43d13a3f0d26_118127_480x0_resize_box_3.PNG 480w, https://Kvn11.github.io/p/intro-to-kernel-exploitation/img/3_hu55927aa20e4b1936546e43d13a3f0d26_118127_1024x0_resize_box_3.PNG 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt="Viewing the values that create the overflow"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="435"
data-flex-basis="1045px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>I wrote the following program in rust to send a big packet that we can then use to debug and follow the flow in gdb:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div class="chroma">
&lt;table class="lntable">&lt;tr>&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code>&lt;span class="lnt"> 1
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt"> 2
