&lt;p>&lt;code>skb_shinfo&lt;/code> will return the &lt;code>skb&lt;/code> endpointer, which could be &lt;code>skb-&amp;gt;head + skb-&amp;gt;end&lt;/code> or &lt;code>skb-&amp;gt;end&lt;/code>.
Eitherway, it will be of type &lt;code>skb_shared_info&lt;/code>, and we need the &lt;code>nr_frag&lt;/code> value to be less than &lt;code>MAX_SKB_FRAGS = #define MAX_SKB_FRAGS (65536/PAGE_SIZE + 1)&lt;/code> (from &lt;code>/include/linux/skbuff.h&lt;/code>).
The actual value will be &lt;code>65536 / 0x1000 + 1 = 17&lt;/code>.
So we do have a max size for our payload, since we don&amp;rsquo;t want it to be split into 17 fragments.
Additionally, this structure cannot have a frag list, which means that it must not be fragmented at all.
This is a tough check, because a packet will be fragmented if it exceeds an interface&amp;rsquo;s MTU, which our large payload is likely to do.
But maybe I don&amp;rsquo;t have to pass this check right away?
Maybe if the same &lt;code>xfrm_state&lt;/code> object is used, then I can create a small packet that passes the checks, and then come back to create another packet that gets copied into the allocated pages?
